---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Blue-dominant Lyman-alpha emission";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Blue-dominant Lyman-α emission</h1>

    <p>
      "Blue-dominant" Lyα refers to double-peaked Lyα line profiles where the blueshifted peak is stronger than the red peak. Such profiles can indicate net inflow of neutral gas along the line of sight, depending on geometry and radiative transfer effects.<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>
    </p>

    <h2>Observational diagnostics</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Double-peaked Lyα with blue-to-total flux ratio B/T &gt; 0.5 is a common operational definition in recent studies (see Mukherjee et al. 2026).<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup></li>
      <li>Spatially-resolved Lyα narrowband imaging can reveal extended, clumpy morphology associated with inflowing streams or CGM clumps.<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup></li>
      <li>Quantitative example (Mukherjee et al. 2026): Voronoi-binned Lyα spectra are best-fit by a clumpy multiphase RT model with B/T ≈ 0.65 and radial clump inflow v_cl ≈ 98 km s⁻¹ (Sect. 3.1–3.2).<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup></li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Why it matters</h2>
    <p>
      Blue-dominant Lyα provides a potentially direct emission-based tracer of gas accretion onto galaxies, complementing absorption-line studies of the CGM and IGM. This diagnostic is rare but useful for identifying inflow in faint, high-redshift systems (Mukherjee et al. 2026). In the MXDF system, the Lyα peak is spatially offset by ≈0.66" from the continuum peak and is embedded in a ≈4 cMpc filament, supporting a cosmic-web inflow interpretation.<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>
    </p>

    <p>
      Additional quantitative details from Mukherjee et al. (2026): the best-fit clumpy radiative-transfer solution produces a blue-to-total flux ratio B/T ≈ 0.65 across the Voronoi bins where the blue-dominant profile is detected, and the model favours radial inflow of neutral clumps with characteristic velocity v_cl ≈ 98 km s⁻¹. The Lyα emission is spatially extended and clumpy on scales resolved by MUSE, with a measured offset of ≈0.66 arcsec between the primary continuum and the Lyα surface-brightness peak, and the system sits within a ≈4 cMpc filament traced in the MXDF field (Mukherjee et al. 2026).<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>
    </p>

    <h2>See also</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/cosmic-web-gas-accretion" text="Cosmic-web gas accretion" /></li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/clumpy-multiphase-radiative-transfer" text="Clumpy radiative-transfer models" /></li>
    </ul>

    <div class="references">
      <h2>References</h2>
      <ol>
        <li id="ref1">Mukherjee, T., Li, Z., Zafar, T., et al. 2026, arXiv:2603.11411, "BLUEPRINT: Blue-dominant Lyman-alpha (Lyα) emission as an evidence of gas inflow in ultra-low-mass galaxies at z = 3".</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

  </main>
</Base>
